is I","Lactogenesis II","Mammogenesis","Involution"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stages of breast development and lactation follow a specific sequence:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the development and growth of breast tissue during puberty and pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactogenesis I\u003C/strong\u003E (secretory differentiation) occurs during pregnancy when the breast tissue develops secretory capability\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactogenesis II\u003C/strong\u003E (secretory activation) is the onset of copious milk production after delivery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactopoiesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the maintenance of established milk production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInvolution\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when milk production ceases and the breast returns to a non-secretory state\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGalactopoiesis is primarily maintained by prolactin and the regular removal of milk from the breast. This stage continues as long as milk is being regularly removed from the breast through nursing or expression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lactogenesis II refers to the onset of copious milk production after delivery","Galactopoiesis refers to the maintenance of established milk production","The stages of breast development and lactation follow a specific sequence: mammogenesis, lactogenesis I (secretory differentiation), lactogenesis II (secretory activation), and galactopoiesis"],"references":["Li S, Wupuer T, Hou R. Factors Influencing Delayed Onset of Lactogenesis: A Scoping Review. Int J Gen Med. 2024 May 21;17:2311-2326. doi: 10.2147/IJGM.S452108. PMID: 38799202; PMCID: PMC11127660","Pillay J, Davis TJ. Physiology, Lactation. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29763156","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16185"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T10:30:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T10:30:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8876"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64248"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",